The `EXPECT_EXIT` macro checks that the enclosed statement causes the program to exit with the specified return code. The `exit_predicate` uses predefined predicates like `ExitedWithCode` to match the expected exit status. The `expected_message` matches the expected output to stderr before the program exits.

If you plan to run multiple death tests in your program, ensure that threads are not interfering with each other by setting the death test style to `"threadsafe"` using `::testing::FLAGS_gtest_death_test_style = "threadsafe"`, or by running your tests with `--gtest_death_test_style=threadsafe` command-line flag.

Please note that death tests can be more expensive in terms of performance and may require specific considerations depending on the platform and test environment.

