Array result1 = (*arr) * 15;
Array result2 = 15 * (*arr);
```

Make sure to declare this new operator function in a place where it can be seen by any code that needs to perform such a multiplication. If this operator overloading function is not declared in the same header file as the `Array` class definition, you will have to include the header file where it is declared in any `.cpp` files that do the multiplication.

To implement a universal `operator*` that allows multiplication with an `Array` object on either the left-hand or the right-hand side of the multiplication, you would define two overloads: one as a member function for when the `Array` is on the left-hand side, and one as a non-member function for when the integer is on the left-hand side. 

