This test constructs the string using `std::stringstream`, writes the element values into the stream separated by spaces, and then uses `str()` to get the entire contents of the stream as a `std::string`. Calling `c_str()` on this `std::string` gives you a `const char*`, which can be used with `EXPECT_STREQ` for comparison against the literal expected C-string.

Please note, `EXPECT_STREQ` is used instead of `EXPECT_EQ` because it is specifically designed to compare C-strings.

This approach ensures that the contents of the stream are placed into a C-string without creating additional string variables, but you're still leveraging the `std::string` type temporarily to capture the content from the stream safely. The string's lifetime must encompass the use of the C-string pointer derived from it to avoid dangling pointers.
